      "Text": "    June 13 (Reuters) - Black children in foster care in the  United States are less likely to be adopted into a family than  children from other races and laws designed to rectify the  imbalance are failing, according to a new report.      Following are some facts about adoption in the United  States:           * Between 130,000 and 140,000 children are adopted each  year. Half of these are adopted by step-parents as new  relationships are formed.      * Around 20,000 children are adopted from abroad each year,  the majority of whom are adopted transracially.      * Between 50,000 and 60,000 children are adopted from  foster care each year, mostly by a parent or parents of the  same race.      * Black children are under-represented among children  adopted from foster care relative to the number of children  waiting in foster care for adoption.      * White children, who make up 58 percent of children in  U.S. society, represent 38 percent of those in foster care but  45 percent of those adopted, according to fiscal year 2006  figures.      * Black children make up 15 percent of total number of  children in the United States but represent 32 percent of those  in foster care and 27 percent of the total number adopted.      * Hispanic children make up 19 percent of children in  society, 20 percent of those waiting for adoption and 19  percent of those adopted.      * The two main laws governing the placement of children in  transracial adoption are the Multiethnic Placement Act of 1994  and the Removal of Barriers to Interethnic Adoption Provisions  of 1996.      (Source: Evan B. Donaldson Adoption Institute and U.S.  Department of Health and Human Services)   (Writing by Matthew Bigg; Editing by John O'Callaghan)   ((matt.bigg@reuters.com; +1 404 992-5745; Reuters Messaging:  matt.bigg.reuters.com@reuters.net))  Keywords: USA ADOPTION/FACTS        ",
