      "Text": "    SINGAPORE, April 25 (Reuters) - Singapore's state-owned  television was fined S$15,000 ($11,040) by the country's censor  for promoting gay lifestyle by airing a programme that showed a  gay couple and their adopted baby, a newspaper said on Friday.      The Straits Times reported that Singapore's Media Development  Authority said the episode of home and decor series Find and  Design, in which the host helped the couple decorate a nursery,  'normalises and promotes a gay lifestyle'.      The pro-government newspaper said the censor had also  objected to scenes of the couple and their baby as well as the  host's acknowledgement of them as a family, because it broke a  rule 'which disallows programmes that promote, justify or  glamorise gay lifestyles'.      Under Singapore law, homosexuality is illegal and a man who  is found to have committed an act of 'gross indecency' with  another man can be jailed for up to two years, though  prosecutions are rare.      Authorities have banned gay festivals and censored gay films  in the past, saying homosexuality should not be advocated as a  lifestyle. But, despite the official ban, Singapore has a  thriving gay scene.   (Reporting by Jan Dahinten; Editing by Sanjeev Miglani)   ((jan.dahinten@thomsonreuters.com; +65 6403 5659; Reuters  Messaging: jan.dahinten.reuters.com@reuters.net))   ($1=1.359 Singapore Dollar)  Keywords: SINGAPORE GAY/       ",
