      "Text": "    By Peter Murphy      SAO PAULO, Aug 11 (Reuters) - Higher temperatures caused by  global warming will reduce land available in Brazil to plant  its most important crops and push its coffee production back  toward the more frost-prone south, a study showed on Monday.      By 2020, the total area suitable for planting soy, the  country's most valuable agricultural export, could fall by  one-quarter, while land suited to coffee production could fall  by nearly 10 percent, the study said.      The research was conducted by the Centre for Meteorological  and Climatic Research Applied to Agricultural of the University  of Campinas in Sao Paulo state, in partnership with federal  agricultural research institute, Embrapa.      'Global warming could bring about a significant change to  Brazil's agricultural map, causing a reduction in productive  areas and revenue losses of around 7.4 billion reais ($4.6  billion) in 2020,' a summary of the research said.      The calculations, based on two scenarios of temperature --  a rise of between 2 and 5.4 degrees Celsius, or a rise of  between 1.4 and 3.8 degrees C -- referred to the amount of land  suitable for production of the crops, and not the land actually  planted with them at present.      The study said soy production in the Latin American country  could suffer 4 billion reais in losses in 2020, nearly  one-quarter of the total value of the crop produced in 2006 and  land suited to the crop could fall by 40 percent by 2070.      It said coffee production in the world's top grower may  have to shift from its southeastern heartland to more southern  regions, such as Parana state, which coffee farmers abandoned  after a severe frost devastated the crop in the mid-1970s.      'With the forecast climate changes, it's possible that  coffee will not have much chance of surviving in the southeast  and migrate to the southern region,' the summary said.      The total area suited to production of rice and corn could  fall by 10 and 12 percent, respectively, according to the  study.      One winner from global warming, albeit until climate change  would worsen decades later, would be sugar cane. The study said  its ability to survive prolonged dry conditions meant it could   be grown in areas that would no longer be able to support other  crops.      The total cane-planted area has been rising in recent  years, driven by demand for cane-derived ethanol to power  Brazil's fast-growing fleet of 'flex-fuel' cars, which can run  solely on the biofuel or any mixture of it with regular  gasoline.      The study said cane production would become increasingly  dependent on irrigation during the dry season as climate change  bites.      'This (warming) has a 95 percent chance of taking place,'  Hilton Silveira Pinto, coordinator of the study, told Reuters.      'Brazil needs to prepare, and quickly,' he added.     ($1=1.61 reais)   (Additional reporting by Roberto Samora; Editing by Walter  Bagley)   ((peter.murphy@thomsonreuters.com; tel +5511 5644 7736;  peter.murphy.reuters.com@reuters.net))  Keywords: BRAZIL CLIMATE/AGRICULTURE       ",
