      "Text": "    FRANKFURT, Jan 8 (Reuters) - German energy regulator  Bundesnetzagentur said on Tuesday the number of German gas  market zones would be cut to eight by October to boost trading  and make customer switches less expensive and complicated.      The authority's president Matthias Kurth said in a statement  that gas grid operators had responded to calls to link  previously separate zones so as to simplify shipping procedures  and help consumers.      'Our goal to cut the number of such zones to below 10 will  be reached...towards our ambition to create more liquidity and  competition,' Kurth said.      The announcement came a day after two gas network operators,  Bayernets and E.ON Gastransport (EGT) <EONG.DE>, said they would  handle gas from the North Sea coast through to the Alps for  potentially half of Germany's preferred gas type called H-Gas in  one joint zone from October.      This cut the number of zones already to 11 compared with  over 700 two years ago when the gas market had not yet emerged.      The latest move brought about by the regulator will entail  three networks, those of the transport arms of southern German  GVS, Italy's ENI <ENI.MI> and GdF Deutschland <GDF.PA> to be  brought together, the statement said.      Another zone of operator Gas Union would also cease to exist  in its current form in the autumn, when a new gas delivery year  starts, the Bundesnetzagentur said.      Apart from EGT/Bayernets and the new three-party zone, that  would leave zones operated by RWE <RWEG.DE>, Wingas  <BASF.DE><GAZP.MM>, VNG-Ontras, EWE and EVG Muenster and  northern German BEB, which Shell <RDSa.L> and ExxonMobil <XOM.N>  recently agreed to sell to Dutch state company Gasunie.      Wholesale gas traders say the nascent marketplace needs a  few zones as possible allow for quick shipments through the  pipeline grid, which is the basis of a functioning market.      Encouraged by the changes, Germany's energy bourse EEX last  October started trading a gas contract in the BEB and E.ON  zones.   (Reporting by Vera Eckert; editing by James Jukwey)   ((vera.eckert@reuters.com; +49 69 7565 1228; Reuters Messaging:  vera.eckert.reuters.com@reuters.net))    Keywords: GERMANY GAS/REGULATOR       ",
